This does three things:
* `MultilinearMap.fromDirectSumEquiv` (in `LinearAlgebra/MultilinearMap/DirectSum.lean`) calculates `MultilinearMap`s on a family of `DirectSum`s. More precisely, if `Œπ` is a `Fintype`, if `Œ∫ i` is a family of types indexed by `Œπ` and we have a `R`-module `M i j` for every `i : Œπ` and `j : Œ∫ i`, this is the linear equivalence between `Œ† p : (i : Œπ) ‚Üí Œ∫ i, MultilinearMap R (fun i ‚Ü¶ M i (p i)) M'` and `MultilinearMap R (fun i ‚Ü¶ ‚®Å j : Œ∫ i, M i j) M'`.
* `PiTensorProduct.directSum` (in `LinearAlgebra/DirectSum/PiTensorProduct.lean`): the distributivity property of a `PiTensorProduct` with respect to `DirectSum`s in all its arguments.
* `finsuppPiTensorProduct` (in `LinearAlgebra/DirectSum/Finsupp.lean`): If `Œπ` is a `Fintype`, `Œ∫ i` is a family of types indexed by `Œπ` and `M i` is a family of `R`-modules indexed by `Œπ`, then the tensor product of the family `Œ∫ i ‚Üí‚ÇÄ M i` is linearly equivalent to `‚àè i, Œ∫ i ‚Üí‚ÇÄ ‚®Ç[R] i, M i`.


- [x] depends on: #11152
- [x] depends on: #11196
